                                    <p>Although not included in Macalister’s 1945 <hi rend="italic">Corpus</hi>, Westropp (1914, 77) recorded this stone as showing <q>notches on the natural-squared edge and faint traces of straight and slant scores</q>.</p>                                    
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stone is quite weathered and spalled.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>Traces of a possible ogham inscription can be seen on the north-west angle of the pillar</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The strokes near the ground are slanted but only evident on the B side (<foreign xml:lang="ga">Aicme Beithe</foreign>) of the angle.
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                             <origPlace corresp="#findspot" ref="https://www.logainm.ie/ga/1399343">
                                 <placeName type="site">Cross Abbey (<foreign xml:lang="ga">Mainistir na Croise</foreign>)</placeName>, 
                                 <placeName type="townland">Cross (Boyd) (<foreign xml:lang="ga">An Chrois</foreign>)</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Co. Mayo</placeName>
                                <geo>54.208993, -10.083446</geo></origPlace>
                            <origDate></origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found">Westropp (1914, 77) recorded this stone as one of two tall stone pillars, one on either side of a ‘walled burial space, 7 feet wide [2.1m],’ which spanned the width of the church... on the E side of the burial space at Cross Abbey, which was possibly an early Christian church site (<ref target="https://monasticon.celt.dias.ie/2930">Monasticon Hibernicum</ref>).
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">The ogham stone is incorporated into the outer edge of the low E wall of the grave structure, at a distance of 1.1m from the N wall of the church. The base of the stone is flanked on the S, W and N sides by the grave wall; the E face is more or less flush with the external face of the grave wall (<!--<ref source="https://maps.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=???">-->Archaeological Survey of Ireland (ASI) field report<!--</ref>-->). 
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
